                    <body>
                              <pb n="1"/>
                              <p rend="align(right)">
                                        <placeName>Office of the Daily Advertiser</placeName>
                              </p>
                              <p rend="align(right)">
                                        <placeName>Kingston Jamaica</placeName>
                              </p>
                              <p rend="align(right)">
                                        <date>Decr 30<hi rend="sup">th</hi>. 1850</date>
                              </p>
                              <p>
                                        <addressee>Revd. Isaac Leeser</addressee>
                              </p>
                              <p rend="indent(1)">
                                        <placeName>Philadelphia</placeName>
                              </p>
                              <p rend="indent(2)">Dear Sir</p>
                              <p rend="indent(3)">I have now before me your favors<lb/> dated
                                                  <date>October 30<hi rend="sup">th</hi></date>
                                        &amp; <date>Dec 3<hi rend="sup">rd</hi></date> and note
                                        their contents</p>
                              <p rend="indent(3)">Although the fearful scourge<lb/> which has been
                                        doing such dreadful work<lb/> has almost entirely
                                        disappeared from <placeName>Kingston</placeName><lb/> still
                                        things are inst unsettled, not at<lb/>
                                        <placeName>Montego Bay</placeName> and
                                                  <placeName>Falmouth</placeName> the enemy is<lb/>
                                        numbering victims by the hundreds. I am<lb/> therefore
                                        unable to do much on your behalf.<lb/> My agent at
                                                  <placeName>Falmouth</placeName>, <persName>Mr
                                                  Genge<add>?</add> Lyons</persName>, will<lb/> do
                                        his best for you, but at a moment like<lb/> the present I
                                        cannot expect any thing to<lb/> be done. The only
                                        subscribers I have to<lb/> the <hi rend="underline"
                                                  >Advocate</hi> are <persName>Edwd.
                                                  Lucas</persName>, &amp; our friend<lb/>
                                        <persName>Mr M Collas</persName>. You may rely that so soon
                                        as</p>
                              <pb n="2"/>
                              <p><sic>as</sic> it shall please the almighty to remove<lb/>
                                        <add>?</add> our low country, the pestilence I<lb/> shall
                                        not be slow in doing my best for<lb/> you. I have advertised
                                        yr appeal to the<lb/> Jews of the <placeName>United
                                                  States</placeName> and the <placeName>W
                                                  Indies</placeName><lb/> and also the <hi
                                                  rend="underline">Occident</hi>, but no good
                                        has<lb/> resulted, probably from the causes I have<lb/>
                                        stated. But I must candidly confess—<lb/> it is no use
                                        deceiving you. That I do not<lb/> expect that you will
                                        receive much support<lb/> here. I could very easily send
                                        you<lb/> a long list of parties willing to become<lb/> “<hi
                                                  rend="underline">subscribers</hi>” to <hi
                                                  rend="underline">all your works</hi>, but
                                        they<lb/> are of that class which more properly<lb/>
                                        speaking should be called <hi rend="underline"
                                                  >receivers</hi>, as<lb/> the “<hi rend="underline"
                                                  >subscription</hi>” part of the business is
                                        the<lb/> last thing they think of. Such parties<lb/> as I
                                        may order the paper for I shall<lb/> have no difficulty in
                                        procuring pay-<lb/>ment from.</p>
                              <pb n="3"/>
                              <p rend="indent(1)">There is very little stirring in the way of<lb/>
                                        news that will interest you. Poor <persName>Mrs.
                                                  Peixotto</persName>,<lb/> mother of my friend
                                                  <persName>Miss Peixotto</persName>, died from<lb/>
                                        debility consequent on an attack of Cholera<lb/> a couple of
                                        weeks ago, at the age of 62.</p>
                              <p rend="indent(1)">I would advise you that whenever<lb/> you publish
                                        your paper that you address<lb/> it (the 1<hi rend="sup"
                                                  >st</hi> number) to parties here whose<lb/> names
                                        I will send you, with a notice<lb/> that I will receive
                                        subscriptions. Please God<lb/> I will send you something
                                        Jewish from<lb/> here to come out with which shall make<lb/>
                                        the paper interesting and thus catch a few<lb/> subscribers,
                                        if possible.</p>
                              <p rend="indent(1)">A project is on food here to extend<lb/> the
                                        benefits of the “Hebrew National Institution”<lb/> by
                                        providing for the Board and Lodging of<lb/> a certain number
                                        of children and combining<lb/> therewith <del>it</del> an
                                        industrial education. The move-<lb/>-ment was set on foot by
                                        the <persName>Revd Solomon<lb/> Jacobs</persName> who
                                        addressed the Jewish public of the
                                                  <placeName>Island</placeName><lb/> on the
                                        necessity of it, through the <sic>colums</sic> of the<lb/>
                                        Daily</p>
                              <pb n="4"/>
                              <p><hi rend="underline">Daily Advertiser</hi> I send you a copy of
                                        the<lb/> appeal made to the public by the Committee<lb/> who
                                        have taken the matter in hand. To<lb/> save postage I have
                                        enclosed the same<lb/> in a small package of my papers to
                                        your<lb/> address. Perhaps you may notice the<lb/> matter in
                                        the <hi rend="underline">Occident</hi>. I may here
                                        after<lb/> give you some account of a reform I<lb/> am
                                        trying to introduce at our adjunto<lb/> (the English &amp;
                                        German <sic>shool</sic>) I mean a<lb/> reform in the <hi
                                                  rend="underline">Constitution of the Vestry</hi><lb/>
                                        <hi rend="underline">not in the mode of worship</hi></p>
                              <p rend="indent(1)"><persName>Mr <add>?</add></persName> has this
                                        moment left<lb/> me. He desires me to convey his
                                        regards<lb/> so does <persName>Mr Peixotto</persName>,
                                                  <persName>Miss P</persName> and all<lb/> the
                                        family</p>
                              <p rend="indent(3)">I am Dear Sir</p>
                              <p rend="indent(4)">Respectfully yours</p>
                              <p rend="indent(4)">
                                        <persName role="author">Isaac <add>?</add></persName>
                              </p>
                              <p><persName>Miss Peixotto</persName> begs that you<lb/> will be good
                                        enough to com-<lb/>-municate to her friends the demise
                                        of<lb/> her mother and to say that in consequence<lb/> of
                                        her affliction she is unable now to write</p>
                              <div>
